#### New state for conflict detection

```typescript
type ConflictStatus = 'idle' | 'checking' | 'no-path' | 'exists-no-dork' | 'exists-has-dork' | 'error';

const [conflictStatus, setConflictStatus] = useState<ConflictStatus>('idle');
```

#### Debounced check effect

Use a debounced effect that fires when the resolved directory path changes:

```typescript
useEffect(() => {
  // Only check on the configure step
  if (step !== 'configure') return;

  const resolvedPath = directoryOverride || (name ? `${defaultDirectory}/${name}` : '');
  if (!resolvedPath) {
    setConflictStatus('idle');
    return;
  }

  setConflictStatus('checking');

  const timer = setTimeout(async () => {
    try {
      const result = await transport.browseDirectory(resolvedPath);
      // browseDirectory returns entries for the given path
      // If it succeeds, the path exists. Check for .dork entry.
      const hasDork = result.entries.some((entry) => entry.name === '.dork');
      setConflictStatus(hasDork ? 'exists-has-dork' : 'exists-no-dork');
    } catch {
      // If browseDirectory throws, the path likely doesn't exist
      // or there's a permission error. Distinguish by error type.
      setConflictStatus('no-path');
    }
  }, 500);

  return () => clearTimeout(timer);
}, [step, directoryOverride, name, defaultDirectory, transport]);
```

Note: `browseDirectory` returns entries for the given path. If the path doesn't exist, it throws. If it exists, we check the entries for a `.dork` subdirectory.

For the error case (permission denied), we need more nuanced handling. Update the catch block:

```typescript
catch (err) {
  const message = err instanceof Error ? err.message : '';
  if (message.includes('EACCES') || message.includes('permission')) {
    setConflictStatus('error');
  } else {
    // Path doesn't exist — will be created
    setConflictStatus('no-path');
  }
}
```

